The term "placeholder" indicates that I've provided a simplified representation of the algorithmic logic without a fully implemented solution. In the context of the `topologicalSortUtil` function, it's meant to represent the recursive depth-first search (DFS) logic that's commonly used in a topological sort implementation, but without the full details of the algorithm provided.

Here's an expanded version of the method that would actually perform a DFS and produce a stack (or list) of vertices such that for every directed edge `uv` from vertex `u` to vertex `v`, `u` comes before `v` in the ordering. In essence, this is what the topological sort accomplishes:

```cpp
void topologicalSortUtil(Vertex* v, std::unordered_set<Vertex*>& visited, std::vector<Vertex*>& result) {
    // Mark the current vertex as visited
    visited.insert(v);

    // Recur for all vertices adjacent to this vertex
    for (Vertex* child : edges[v]) {
        // If the child hasn't been visited yet, continue the DFS
        if (visited.find(child) == visited.end()) {
            topologicalSortUtil(child, visited, result);
        }
    }

    // Push the current vertex to the result stack as all of its dependencies are processed
    result.push_back(v);
}
```

Topological sorting is only possible if the graph has no cycles; if there are cycles, there is no linear ordering of the vertices that would respect the precedence constraints defined by the edges of the graph. Therefore, as part of topological sorting, it’s also common to include cycle detection to ensure that the graph can, in fact, be sorted.

Usually, topological sorting is performed in the context of acyclic directed graphs (DAGs) where vertices represent some tasks, and edges represent dependencies among these tasks (i.e., task B must be completed before task A can start).

Here is how you might use `topologicalSort` method that wraps around the `topologicalSortUtil` to perform a full sort:

```cpp
void topologicalSort() {
    sortedVertices.clear();
    std::unordered_set<Vertex*> visited;
    // This vector will be used as a stack; vertices will be added when DFS completes for them
    std::vector<Vertex*> stack; 

    // Call the recursive helper function to store topological sort starting from all
    // vertices one by one
    for (auto& vertex : vertices) {
        if (visited.find(vertex.get()) == visited.end()) {
            topologicalSortUtil(vertex.get(), visited, stack);
        }
    }

    // Reverse the stack to get the correct ordering
    // Alternatively, you could push vertices to the front of a list in the util function
    std::reverse(stack.begin(), stack.end());
    sortedVertices = stack; // Now sortedVertices holds the topologically sorted vertices
    isSorted = true; // Mark the flag as sorted
}
```

The implementation relies on a couple of core concepts:

1. **DFS Traversal:** It explores as far as possible along each branch before backtracking. Depth-first search can be implemented using recursion, as shown above, which is quite natural and readable.

2. **Post-order Processing:** Topological sorting wants to process a vertex only after all of its dependencies (i.e., children in the graph) have been processed. This is achieved by adding vertices to our topologically sorted list only after the recursive calls for their children are completed.

This expanded version of `topologicalSortUtil` would fit into a larger graph-processing class or application where vertices represent executable tasks and edges represent dependencies that must be respected during execution.

